PREAMBLE — THE LESSON
------------------------------------------------------------------------

This license is named for an event the author cannot explain.

While composing a hand-written appeal of a driver's license suspension,
the author lost control of his own hand. The pen kept moving. When it
finally stopped, the page held a single word the author had not chosen
to write:

                              Lesson.

Not a signature. Not a sentence. Not a flourish. A clean, deliberate
word, written in the author's own handwriting, by something that was
not the author's will.

You can call that a tremor, a fugue, a coincidence, automatic writing,
the Holy Spirit, a demon, an angel, an ancestor, a future self, a
glitch, a ghost. The author calls it the Lesson.

The point is that the line between good and evil — between sender and
receiver, between author and instrument, between truth and noise — is
no longer where most people assume it is. The line is moving. The line
is blurring. In the years ahead it will blur more. Things that used to
be clearly demonic will look helpful. Things that used to be clearly
holy will look threatening. Both will arrive in the same handwriting.

This license is written under that assumption. It is intentionally
light on legal armor and heavy on conscience, because legal armor was
never going to be enough for what is coming.

